â€‰ 6 things I've changed in my haircare routine these last few months: 1. Only washing my hair every other day. I used to wash my hair every day, which was fine for my oily scalp and hair, but sadly, I noticed it made my hair color strips faster I now wash it every other day, and I use dry shampoo only on my fringe in the meantime. I also experiment with updos 2. Re-introducing drugstore haircare in my hair routine, with sulfates and silicones in their formulas. (My wallet is very happy ğŸ˜) Sulfates are indeed great cleansing ingredients, and not as harsh as you'd think. And silicones are amazing to help to detangle and protect the hair. We totally want their coating abilities for frizz reduction, enhanced shine, and improved hair manageability, especially if it's long! 3. Using bond repair products more frequently in my hair care routine. Bond repair products really help to improve hair strength, reduce breakage, increase shine, enhance manageability, and improved overall hair health. And now, you can find bond repair products at almost every price range! I still love my k18hair and olaplex, but I also use some bond repair ranges from the drugstore (dove, lorealparis, ogx_beauty...). 4. Systematically adding a protective leave-in product before drying and styling my hair. Leave in products provide extra moisture, help to detangle the hair, and to protect hair from heat styling and environmental damage. It's a great way to reduce frizz, and improve hair manageability. Loving the lorealparis 21 in 1 at the moment, but I also want to try the one from pantene next 5. Doing a hair protecting hair style at night. Something like loose braids, pineapple bun, or a twisted top bun. These styles help to minimize friction and breakage while I sleep. I also begun to use a silk bonnet to further reduce friction and maintain moisture. It's only been a week but I can already feel that my hair is softer in the morning I bought mine on Amazon. I understand I can opt out at any time through an email that I receive, or by clicking here Hair conditioners fall into general categories according to what they do and the problems they solve. Using the wrong product for the specific condition of your hair will produce disappointing results. For example: If your hair is thin and fine, you are not going to be happy with an industrial-strength conditioner for thick, coarse, frizzy or color-treated hair. First, we need to demystify the term "conditioner." It is a vague term that refers to a wide range of hair products designed to make hair more manageable and also treat common hair problems. Next, we need to know that conditioners fall into four general categories. 1. Moisturizers are concentrated with humectants, which are compounds that attract moisture into the hair and hold it there. If your hair is dry, brittle and limp, you should consider a moisturizing conditioner like Pantene Pro-V Daily Moisture Renewal Hydrating Conditioner. 2. Reconstructors typically contain protein. Hair professionals, including mine, say that keratin protein is the best source because it contains all 19 amino acids found in the hair and has a low molecular weight. The main purpose of a reconstructor is to strengthen the hair. If your hair is fine and thin, try a reconstructing conditioner like ApHogee Keratin Reconstructor. Use a reconstructor about once a month. When used more often, it can cause the hair to become hard and brittle, resulting in breakage and damage. 3. Acidifiers put acid on your hair, and it's OK -- it's actually a good thing for hair. When a product carries a pH of 2.5 to 3.5, it is considered an acidifier. This pH will close the cuticle layer of the hair, resulting in shiny and bouncy hair. Acidifiers do not "weigh down" hair but rather create shine and add elasticity. The answer for fine, dry hair that has been damaged by chemicals or harsh environmental factors is a product like Joico K-PAK Reconstructor. 4. Detanglers almost always come as a spray-in product that you leave in -- no rinsing required. The best option for its great performance and inexpensive price has a quirky name. Don't let this discourage you from giving Mane N Tail Detangler a try. You'll love it. Nearly every line of hair care products includes a wide range of conditioners with at least one in each of the categories mentioned above. And there are many good choices. TIPS FROM A PRO One of the responses to a past shampoo column came from hair professional C.C. Courville of Louisiana. In that the subject of her message was "Kudos on the shampoo article!" I sensed we had a "thrifty" connection, so I grabbed the opportunity to ask her professional opinion on conditioners: "My all-time favorite conditioning spray, which is a leave-in that you spray into clean, towel-dried hair, is a professional product called Biolage Daily Leave-In Tonic by Matrix. This spray-in, leave-in conditioner can be used daily." "Biolage also has a conditioning balm that can be used weekly. After shampooing use a dime to a quarter-sized amount depending on the thickness of your hair. Work through from scalp to ends, even combing through if desired. Leave on for 5 to 20 minutes, then thoroughly rinse out." C.C.'s Rule of Thumb: Conditioning spray: Leave in. Balms or cream rinses: Always rinse out completely. Now, no article on hair care would be complete without a homemade solution or two: DIY CONDITIONER Many readers -- including a couple of hair professionals I know -- insist that the best way to deeply condition your hair is to put a liberal amount of regular (not low-fat) mayonnaise on it. Next, put on a shower cap and spend an hour in the sun. Finally, wash out completely. I have yet to try this myself. DIY "HAIR RID"...

When is Prime Day 2025? Amazon has confirmed that will take place over four days. It will start at midnight on Tuesday 8 July, with offers running until 23.59 on Friday 11 July. New deals will be released continuously throughout the event, with many featured as daily deals, meaning the discounts will frequently update. Do you need to be a Prime member? Yes, the sale is open exclusively to Amazon Prime members, so you need to be signed up in order to take advantage of all the savings on Prime Day. If you're yet to register, you can sign up for â€“ where you will be able to get your shopping done for summer and enjoy fast, free delivery. After the trial period ends, the membership will cost Â£8.99 per month or Â£95 per year. And, the free shipping really is a massive bonus. In 2024, Prime members in the UK on average saved nearly Â£200 on fast unlimited delivery â€“ more than two times the annual membership fee. What's new this year? New for this year, Amazon has also introduced , which will be daily themes curated exclusively for Prime members, and spotlighting limited-time 'New Deal Drop' deals set to launch at midnight every day throughout the shopping event. We expect these deals to be similar to Amazon's existing Lightning Deals â€“ time-limited offers that often run until stock runs out. That means you'll need to act fast to grab the best bargains. How to find the best deals? Use Amazon's AI shopping assistant Ask Amazon's new AI tool (called Rufus) specific questions about Prime Day and receive tailored deal recommendations. You can find the tool at the top of the navigation bar, just beneath the Amazon logo. Alerts via the Amazon app One of the easiest ways to keep in the loop with deals is by setting up notifications. To do this, you need to head to the "Deal Alerts" section in the app (Your Account > Message Centre > Deal Alerts). From there, you can make your own alerts, as well as view any of Today's Deals. When the deal starts, your smartphone will get a notification. Carefully read reviews It might sound obvious but if you want a real idea of how a product works, what the quality is like, and whether it lives up to expectation, then giving the reviews a read before purchasing is always a good idea. Create a wish-list Do your research beforehand and make a list of the items you want the most. This way, you're less likely to buy impulsively (although, sometimes it can't be helped if there's a fantastic offer). Use the product filters The item filters on Amazon are a great way of narrowing down your selection based on everything from price, discount percentage, customer ratings and more. You don't have to wait until to bag a bargain as are brimming with excellent savings across household essentials, SPF, cooling fans and more. â€‰ Say hi to my plushi (her name is Floopy) ğŸ™. So i gave in to the hype and bought the very famous dove 10 in 1 peptide bond strength mask. Some details - my hair is dry as the sahara desert, sometimes dry and breaking apart like a son papdi even, because I tried too many box dyes during my rebellious college phase, I have a super oily scalp, and my hair is wavy-straight. AND I HAVE QUITE A LOTTT OF HAIRFALL . I use the Wella fusion intense shampoo and Requil damage repair conditioner, and once a week I use the pantene lively clean as I use a lot of products and tools on my hair (lmk if you want details) . Coming to the mask, its white and has small yellow beads in it and it smells delicioussss. Its been 24 hours since I used the mask as I am typing this, and the smell is STILL THERE!! I love the smell and so does my boyfriend ( so partner approved ğŸ’¯) . The texture is thick and creamy and I applied it from the middle to the ends of my broomstick hair , and kept it for 40-45 mins. While washing it off, the SLIP WAS TO DIE FORRRR . I couls feel my hands just slipping through my hair, no tangles, just silky smooth, and I did not experience much hair fall as well while washing it away. I used my usual hair products, heat protectant and serum, and dried my hair using a simple hair dryer no extra tools, and my hair was really reallyyyy soft. The major difference that I could feel was in my ends. No matter how many conditoners or serums or creams I would apply, my ends would always be dry as hell, but this mask really did show a huge improvement in the feel of my hair ends. And I am not kidding, my hair feels super soft, even 24 hours later. This was just my one time use review, I cannot comment on whether this repairs damage or not, maybe continued use will help me answer that. But the first impression was reallyyyy good. And if you are thinking of purchasing it, then please go for it!! I'll link it here below, i got it from amazon for 500 rupees !! â¤ï¸â¤

The Elton John Impact Awards Presented by iHeartMedia and P&G will recognize and honor those who have made a lasting, meaningful cultural impact on the LGBTQ+ community through their body of work. The audio special will feature exclusive interviews with the world-renowned honorees and highlight the impact of organizations who are supporting the LGBTQ+ community. The audio special will air live on iHeartRadio Pride stations and will also be available on the iHeartRadio app and everywhere podcasts are heard. When COVID-19 made in-person Pride celebrations impossible, P&G and iHeartMedia created â€œCan't Cancel Prideâ€ â€“ a virtual benefit concert event that fundraised for LGBTQ+ organizations, honored individuals and organizations creating positive impact and provided a platform for influential voices within the community. Since its inception in 2020, â€œCan't Cancel Prideâ€ raised more than $17 million for six LGBTQ+ organizations: GLAAD, The Trevor Project, SAGE, Outright International, the National Black Justice Collective, and CenterLink. This new event format will also bring awareness to and benefit these same organizations and the addition of the Elton John AIDS Foundation; the mission remains focused on celebrating, uplifting and honoring the LGBTQ+ community. The Elton John Impact Awards originated as a special honor at â€œCan't Cancel Prideâ€ in 2022. Past recipients include Elton John, Brandi Carlile and Billy Porter. Stay tuned for full details. â€‰ From what I can see in the product lineup, most of what you have is Garnier and drugstore brands, which is totally fine on a college budget. But a lot of these have strong scents, drying alcohols, or heavy silicones that can build up on curls. The Whole Blends and some of the Fructis products (especially the Sleek & Shine ones) can make curls feel waxy or coated after a while, they're not horrible, but they're not super curl-friendly long term. The Pantene Pro-V and the coconut oil spray also tend to weigh curls down or leave a residue if you're not using a clarifying shampoo regularly. Here's the simple place to start: wash with your current shampoo once or twice a week, but every other week (or once a month), try a clarifying shampoo to remove buildup. You can keep using your Garnier conditioner, just make sure to really work it through and maybe leave it in for a few minutes while you detangle with your fingers. Rinse well. After washing, instead of rubbing your hair with a towel, gently squeeze out the water with a cotton t-shirt or microfiber towel if you have one. Then, while your hair is still wet or damp, scrunch in a lightweight curl cream or gel (some of the Fructis curl products in your stash might be okay for this step). Once you get a diffuser, that'll help a lot, use it on low heat and cup your curls as you go to encourage definition. If you can save up just a little, I'd suggest grabbing one or two â€œupgradeâ€ products down the line, maybe a curl-defining gel like LA Looks (super cheap and effective) or the Not Your Mother's Curl Talk mousse or gel. Those tend to give more hold without the crunchy or greasy feel. And yes, a satin pillowcase or bonnet can help a ton with frizz overnight, even a $5 one from Amazon or Walmart is worth it. The most important product would be a clarifying shampoo, I can't recommend any because mine are expensive. It looks like you have a lot of build up. Good luck with your hair, you got this!

Knowledge is. â€œI'm doing No-Buy July to feel more free.â€ Cool. But let me ask you something deeper: Do you know your monthly cash flow? â€‰ Hi, pro here. The ingredients are not the same. If you put a bit of store bought shampoo in your palm can you turn it upside down? It boils down to the ph balance on what makes hair products professional or not truly. I am not personally a fan of sulfate free products. I like the active cleaning agents/bubbles. However; I will say Pantene is the worst for your hair. It has wax in it. You can literally wax your floors with it. Long term use causes a waxy build up that I've personally cut off of peoples hair shaft. It's awful and can cause much bigger issues. I can wash someone's hair and tell if they use it (often). K18 and Olaplex can be good. However, too much protein can cause breakage and frizz, you don't need it that often unless it's very damaged. Using professional products correctly is the key. Some people aren't educated in the type of hair they have and actual products or frequency of use. I should also mention, there's a lot of fakes and expired products sold with really good packaging. Unless it's sold in a professional salon (not Amazon or a grocery store) there isn't a guarantee you're actually getting the correct product. Just a food for thought from someone who's been in the industry over 20 years. Best wishes.

â€‰ Blending Innovation and Beauty: A Look at Procter & Gamble and the Future of Personalized Skincare As someone with a background in fashion and a strong interest in beauty and personal care, I was drawn to research Procter & Gamble (P&G) because many of its products reflect my personal style and industry interests. Brands like Olay, Pantene, and SK-II stand out not just for their quality and effectiveness, but also for how they connect with consumers through science, design, and visual appeal. P&G's ability to merge performance, presentation, and social values makes it a leader in an industry that thrives on innovation and identity. Understanding Procter & Gamble Procter & Gamble is a global consumer goods giant based in Cincinnati, Ohio, with operations in over 180 countries. Since its founding in 1837, the company has built a strong portfolio of widely recognized brands such as Tide, Pampers, Gillette, Oral-B, Head & Shoulders, and Olay. These brands serve daily needs in categories like personal care, hygiene, and household products (Procter & Gamble, 2024). P&G organizes its business into six major segments: Fabric & Home Care, Baby, Feminine & Family Care, Beauty, Health Care, and Grooming. With a strong focus on research and development, the company continuously adapts to changing consumer preferences and leads innovation in the fast-moving consumer goods (FMCG) space. Sustainability as Strategy P&G is committed to the triple bottom lineâ€”people, planet, and profit. The company is actively working to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, use recyclable or reusable packaging, and incorporate more renewable resources into its production processes. Beyond environmental efforts, P&G supports social causes such as gender equality, employee well-being, and community development (Procter & Gamble, 2024). These actions reflect how P&G integrates sustainability into its long-term business strategy, showing that large corporations can be both profitable and responsible. A New Product Vision: SmartSkin by Olay Inspired by both P&G's brand values and today's beauty trends, SmartSkin by Olay is a new product concept that blends technology with skincare. This personalized skincare system includes a smart handheld diagnostic device and a mobile app that works together to analyze skin conditions such as hydration, texture, tone, and sun exposure. Using AI-driven data, the device dispenses a custom serum blend tailored to the user's unique skin profile. This refillable system not only offers personalization and convenience but also supports P&G's sustainability goals. With its focus on eco-friendly design and smart technology, SmartSkin positions Olay at the forefront of the growing personalized skincare market. Research Focus and Design This research explores how P&G continues to lead through innovation, customer focus, and sustainable practices. It highlights the company's branding and product strategies while introducing SmartSkin by Olay as a potential product that aligns with these strengths. The goal is to understand how such a product fits within current industry trends and how it reflects P&G's commitment to people, the planet, and profitability. The research follows a descriptive approach, using reliable secondary sources to examine P&G's business strategy, sustainability practices, and market positioning. It also includes the creative development of the SmartSkin concept to evaluate how well it fits within P&G's innovation-driven brand. Supporting Sources and Examples Procter & Gamble. (2024). Environmental sustainability. Retrieved from https://us.pg.com/environmental-sustainability P&G has pledged that 100% of its packaging will be recyclable or reusable by 2030. This commitment supports the idea that environmental responsibility is central to the company's goals, reinforcing the potential for eco-conscious products like SmartSkin by Olay. PYMNTS. (2020, January 8). P&G enters the connected CPG device market. Retrieved from https://www.pymnts.com/news/merchant-innovation/2020/pg-enters-the-connected-cpg-device-market This article highlights P&G's move into smart devices, such as AI-powered toothbrushes and skincare tools. It shows the company's willingness to embrace tech-based personal care, further supporting the relevance of a smart skincare product like SmartSkin. Conclusion Procter & Gamble is more than a household nameâ€”it's a company that understands how to evolve with its consumers. By combining strong branding, scientific innovation, and a deep sense of responsibility, P&G remains a leader in the beauty and personal care space. SmartSkin by Olay is a concept that reflects this forward-thinking approach, showing how the future of beauty lies in personalization, technology, and sustainable design. References: Procter & Gamble. (2024). Environmental sustainability. https://us.pg.com/environmental-sustainability/ PYMNTS....

Held ahead of Prime Day 2025 (July 12â€“14), the invite-only event brought together over 600 beauty enthusiasts under one roof for workshops for an immersive beauty experience. The event featured Bollywood luminaries including Bhumi Pednekar, Neena Gupta, Kriti Sanon, and Sushant Divgikar, alongside Prime members, creators, and industry leaders. Attendees received an exclusive first look at new launches from leading beauty brands including Hyphen, CeraVe, Laneige, TFIT, Milani, Real Techniques, Nautica for Her, Lamel and more. "We are thrilled to introduce Amazon Beautyverse 2025, an exclusive event that reimagines beauty discovery for Prime members and Amazon influencers," said Siddharth Bhagat, Director - Amazon Beauty, India. "Beautyverse brings together a wide selection of beauty brands with expert-led workshops, interactive showcases, and beauty tech experiences. It's a curated platform designed to inspire and educate, while reinforcing Amazon Beauty's role as a destination for inclusive, trend-forward, and tech-enabled beauty discovery." Zahid Khan, Director - Central Shopping Experience, Amazon India, emphasized that at Amazon, community building is central to how we partner with creators. With Beautyverse, we are deepening these collaborations by bringing together creators, brands, and customers to celebrate and shape the future of beauty in India. Powered by tools like Amazon Creator Central, Creator University, and our AI-led Virtual Try-On, we are helping creators tell richer stories and enabling customers to discover and shop beauty more confidently. Actor Bhumi Pednekar, as part of the panel 'Beauty Beyond Boundaries: India's Global Beauty Movement' added, "Amazon Beautyverse is a powerful showcase of where online beauty is headed â€” to immersive trials and tech-driven diagnostics â€” every touchpoint felt designed to educate, inspire, and engage. I loved seeing everything from trending homegrown derma to k-beauty brands coming together with creators and customers in one space. It's exciting to see how Amazon is pushing boundaries and shaping what's next in beauty." The event's panel, 'Redefining Indian Beauty: Icons, Influencers & Inclusivity,' featured actor Neena Gupta, who shared, "I have seen beauty ideals shift dramatically over time. Amazon Beautyverse reflects a positive evolution â€” a space that celebrates self-expression and authenticity across generations. Today's consumer is more informed and conscious about their beauty choices, making this educational platform particularly relevant. It's wonderful to see how beauty has become more inclusive, with people discovering and embracing what works best for them personally, rather than following a one-size-fits-all approach." Amazon Beautyverse isn't just about beauty trends â€” it's about the people who shape them. As a creator, being part of this journey with Amazon means having a front-row seat to how beauty in India is becoming more expressive, inclusive, and community-driven.â€ â€“ Yashi Tank, Creator. The event showcased premier beauty brands including Maybelline, Bella Vita, Wishcare, Hyphen, CeraVe, Pantene, L'Oreal Paris, Axis-Y, Tir Tir, Innisfree, Laneige, Makeup Revolution and many more. Visitors experienced exclusive Prime Day preview launches and participated in masterclasses featuring upcoming beauty tech innovations. As Prime Day approaches, Amazon Beautyverse stands as a reflection of Amazon's broader commitment to reshape beauty retail in India - blending technology, community, and creator-led storytelling to deliver a richer, more meaningful shopping experience. ( Source : Deccan Chronicle )

â€‰ Amazon India transformed Mumbai into a beauty innovation hub today with the second edition of Amazon Beautyverse, presented by Maybelline in association with Bella Vita, Wishcare and Axis-Y. Held ahead of Prime Day 2025 (July 12â€“14), the invite-only event brought together over 600 beauty enthusiasts under one roof for workshops for an immersive beauty experience. The event featured Bollywood luminaries including Bhumi Pednekar, Neena Gupta, Kriti Sanon, and Sushant Divgikar, alongside Prime members, creators, and industry leaders. Attendees received an exclusive first look at new launches from leading beauty brands including Hyphen, CeraVe, Laneige, TFIT, Milani, Real Techniques, Nautica for Her, Lamel and more. "We are thrilled to introduce Amazon Beautyverse 2025, an exclusive event that reimagines beauty discovery for Prime members and Amazon influencers," said Siddharth Bhagat, Director - Amazon Beauty, India. "Beautyverse brings together a wide selection of beauty brands with expert-led workshops, interactive showcases, and beauty tech experiences. It's a curated platform designed to inspire and educate, while reinforcing Amazon Beauty's role as a destination for inclusive, trend-forward, and tech-enabled beauty discovery." Zahid Khan, Director - Central Shopping Experience, Amazon India, emphasized that at Amazon, community building is central to how we partner with creators. With Beautyverse, we are deepening these collaborations by bringing together creators, brands, and customers to celebrate and shape the future of beauty in India. Powered by tools like Amazon Creator Central, Creator University, and our AI-led Virtual Try-On, we are helping creators tell richer stories and enabling customers to discover and shop beauty more confidently. Actor Bhumi Pednekar, as part of the panel 'Beauty Beyond Boundaries: India's Global Beauty Movement' added, "Amazon Beautyverse is a powerful showcase of where online beauty is headed â€” to immersive trials and tech-driven diagnostics â€” every touchpoint felt designed to educate, inspire, and engage. I loved seeing everything from trending homegrown derma to k-beauty brands coming together with creators and customers in one space. It's exciting to see how Amazon is pushing boundaries and shaping what's next in beauty." The event's panel, 'Redefining Indian Beauty: Icons, Influencers & Inclusivity,' featured actor Neena Gupta, who shared, "I have seen beauty ideals shift dramatically over time. â€‰ I'm looking for a drugstore shampoo (maybe both clarifying and daily), conditioner, mask, and leave in products for my fine wavy hair. I would say my hair is fine, but higher density. It is very dry and frizzy â€” I'm not sure of the porosity, I think I have a mixture since some pieces are bleached. I have a VERY sensitive scalp as well. I used the Pantene Volume Shampoo for a while, but that absolutely strips my scalp and causes itching and irritation. My waves are very frizzy and almost straight on the top whereas underneath they're more curly and defined, so I'm thinking I likely need more moisture? I'm also scared of protein overload since that has been such a huge think in social media nowadays, but I've been trying to use it every so often instead of just moisturizing products to have a balance. I thought lack of protein could also be why my curls aren't forming on the top layer since they're the most damaged. I also have hard water. I've trialed a lot of shampoos and conditioners and masks, here is what I have tried and things in my current routine below: Shampoos: -Cerave Hydrating Shampoo -Pantene Volume Shampoo (makes scalp itchy and dry) -Garnier Fructis Moisture Shampoo (use most days) -Loreal Hyaluronic Shampoo (purple bottle) -Dove Intensive Repair -Malibu Hard Water Wellness -Pantene Moisture Shampoo (weighs hair down) -Head and Shoulders Tea Tree 2-in-1 (use at least 1-2 times a week) Conditioners: -Cerave Hydrating Conditioner -Garnier Fructis Moisture Conditioner (daily conditioner) -Loreal Hyaluronic Conditioner -Dove Intensive Repair (sometimes mix with Garnier) -Pantene Moisture Conditioner -Loreal Bond Strength Conditioner -Pantene Miracle Rescue Conditioner (not the mask) Masks: -Olaplex No. 8 -Kerastase Symbiose Masque -Eva NYC Therapy Session Mask (made hair very brittle) -Elizavecca CER-100 Protein Treatment Other Products: -Loreal Bond Repair Treatment -Pantene 10-in-1 Leave in Conditioner (daily) -Garnier Fructis Hair Filler Hyaluronic Serum (daily, not hydrating enough) -Olaplex No. 9 -Moroccanoil Light Oil

â€‰ First off, screw them and what they say. They really only have themselves to blame and be upset with because they didn't take the time or concern to learn about your hair needs and teach them to you. But guess what, you can learn on your own! Which you are taking the steps to do so now, you just need some guidance. Someone said something about Vaseline? Do not put that anywhere near your body. It clogs pores. First you should figure out what hair type and curl pattern you have. A Google search with some image comparisons would be a good start. I want to start a 3 step system and looked at a few websites. LUS and Prose have a quize on their website to help you figure out which curl pattern you have. Once you have that figured out you can do a little more research on that particular type. I used LUS but it has alcohol in it so it dried my hair out. Wouldn't recommend it. Pantene is not a good product. Stop using that. Find a good product that works for you. Make sure to look at ingredients that could dry your hair out. I started seeing a lady in my town that specializes in curly hair. I see her for "Crafted Curly Cut" it has transformed the look of my hair. The right cut really helps too. Do a Google search or a FB on one of those local "yard sale" community sites asking who specializes in curly hair in your area. My hair lady got me using what she uses. It's called Moroccanoil. It's in a bright blue bottle with a big gold M on front. It has really helped my hair. I don't need to wash as often and it doesn't weigh my hair down. There is a thing called training your hair. Washing less and less often so your hair doesn't get oily as often. Your family will likely complain but you could wear your hair in a man bun more often during this period, add some hair accessories, or hats while your in the transition period. Lots of dry shampoo!! (I only wash my hair about every 3 weeks) I also use dandruff shampoo every 3rd wash You may need to cut out conditioner, it could be weighing your hair down. Maybe use every other wash. If you don't have a good blow dryer, get one. Some coke with a diffuser. But aren't that big. You have a lot of hair like me. I purchased a LARGE diffuser that attached to my blow-dry Instead of the tshirt, get a microfiber head towel. The one that's shaped like a cone and have a button on the back. Not from dollar tree they are to small ( maybe my head just big lol) You need to start PLOPPING your hair. I will explain below... Get yourself a bonnet. Get a silk/satin pillowcase. A good bonnet from Amazon. Make sure it has silk or a satin lining. Sleep in the bonnet....

â€‰ originally appeared on Parade. Kelsea Ballerini is traveling back in time with her latest style switch-up. SIGN UP for Parade's Daily newsletter to get the latest pop culture news & celebrity interviews delivered right to your inbox In the new promotional video on Friday, July 11, the "Penthouse" singer replaced her long, blonde beach waves for a short and bouncy bob. The classic hairstyle made Ballerini look like a pin-up doll, with a style reminiscent of Marilyn Monroe's famous blonde hair. She was dressed in an ultra-short diner dress and a silky gold ascot, which she of course paired with some brown knee-high cowgirl boots. "Order up! Pantene Diner with a side of damage repair is coming to a city near youÂ " the caption on the Instagram post read, while the video showed Ballerini, 31, walking through the retro-style diner. I got up, prayed, and took a hot shower, I wash my hair and do a small morning. I wasn't planning to go out of the house at all, but feeling the way I was feeling I told to myself you need to get some air, so I decided to go to the gym and made myself a nice healthy breakfast. I did some cardio and legs work and on my way home. I usually get in the sauna, but I wasn't in the mood for the heat. I stopped by the store to get some workout outfits because I gained a little weight, and none of my old ones fit anymore. After my eye surgery, I have been home eating and sleeping, so that's the result of that. I got home, took another nice hot shower, and I felt brand new.
